    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so if it is nitrogen, how do i fix the soil? do i need to change the ph or something to help it absorb better?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you suspect nitrogen deficiency, you're looking to give your tomato plants a good, steady supply of that vital green stuff! Nitrogen is the big fuel for leafy growth, and you can usually fix this by applying a nitrogen-rich fertilizer. You don't necessarily need to overhaul your entire soil pH right away, though keeping it in the slightly acidic to neutral range (around 6.0 to 7.0) is generally best for tomatoes. A quick fix is often a liquid feed, like one containing ammonium nitrate, applied according to the package directions.\n\nHowever, if you're worried about the soil itself, a slow-release organic amendment like compost or aged manure can slowly build up the nitrogen over time, which is less sudden than a chemical blast. Think of it like this: a quick fertilizer is like a sudden, loud shout of \"FEED ME!\" while compost is like a steady, comforting murmur of \"EAT THIS, LITTLE ONE.\" If your soil is too alkaline, it can lock up nutrients, making them unavailable, which is a real problem, but start with the feeding first.",
